      • getResult

        public java.util.Iterator<java.util.Map.Entry<java.lang.String,java.lang.Object>> getResult()
        Description copied from interface: QueryBuilderFinalizer
        Executes the previously built query.

        Usage example: 

         Iterator<Entry<String, Object>> iterator = tx.find().where("name").contains("hello").getResult();
 // now simply iterate over the result...
 while (iterator.hasNext()) {
        Entry<String, Object> entry = iterator.next();
        String key = entry.getKey();
        Object value = entry.getValue();
        // ... do something with them
 }

        WARNING:
        The result set of this method will contain all key-value combinations that match the query. If the query considers more than one keyspace, then the returned keys are not guaranteed to be unique. The reason is that a single key can simultaneously appear in multiple keyspaces with potentially different values. To disambiguate this situation, please consider using QueryBuilderFinalizer.getQualifiedResult() if you are dealing with queries across keyspaces.

        Specified by:
        getResult in interface QueryBuilderFinalizer
        Returns:
        An iterator over all key-value pairs that match the query. May be empty, but never null.
        See Also:
        QueryBuilderFinalizer.getQualifiedResult()

 }

        WARNING: The returned iterator delivers the values for all key-value pairs that match the query. It is not guaranteed that any of the values will be unique!
